The apparent morbidity rates in cattle (percentages) in the 4 countries are:
Greece - 1.2; Bulgaria - 2.1; FYR Macedonia - 1.3; Romania - 20.2.

The strikingly high BT morbidity in Romanian cattle, apparently caused by the same BTV-4 serotype which traditionally is known to cause clinical disease primarily in sheep, is puzzling.

In the absence of vaccination, losses -- primarily in sheep -- in all affected countries must be heavy. According to a media report from Bulgaria, dated 2 Sep 2014 citing the Ministry of Agriculture: "The number of sheep that had died of bluetongue stood at nearly 6500 towards 1 Sep 2014; the situation concerning goats and cattle was less alarming." For the full media report, see http://www.focus-fen.net/news/2014/09/02/347468/bulgaria-interim-cabinet-to-vote-on-bgn-18-mn-to-tackle-bluetongue-disease-deputy-minister.html. - Mod.AS

